projectInfo.name: Site Mapping Aysaita - Ethiopia
projectInfo.shortDescription:
The UN Refugee Agency (UNHCR) is assisting the Ethiopian government in facing with the influx of refugees. Among other things, the UNHCR manages the establishment of refugee settlement, ensures access to basic facilities and provides humanitarian aid.
UNHCR has requested the assistance of CartONG and its community of volunteers to map several camps along the border that do not yet appear on any map. This involves mapping houses/shelters and roads.
projectInfo.description: Ethiopia is one of the largest country of asylum for refugee of the world and the second largest in Africa, reflecting the fragility and ongoing conflicts in the region. Among the main factors contributing to this situation are the conflict in South Sudan, the prevailing political environment in Eritrea, and the conflict and drought in Somalia. In 2017 Ethiopia offers protection to more than 850,000 refugees - the majority of whom come from neighbourhood countries. Most are hosted in 27 refugee settlements, in which services and opportunities are limited and mainly dependent on humanitarian assistance. The influx of refugees continues, with over 35,000 people coming to seek security and protection within the country's borders over the past year. The UN Refugee Agency (UNHCR) is assisting the Ethiopian government in facing with this influx of refugees. Among other things, it manages the establishment of settlements, ensures access to basic facilities and provides humanitarian aid. This year, a site planner team is in charge of planning the extension of existing camps in northern Ethiopia. The team lacks maps to better understand the current situation and identify the location of future extensions that are both in a safe area and sufficiently close to the existing facilities of the former camps or villages of the host communities. UNHCR has requested the assistance of CartONG and its community of volunteers to map these camps, which do not yet appear on any map. This involves mapping houses/shelters and roads. *Watch Philipp's video, UNHCR's site planner, he explains how he will use the map in the field* **HERE**
projectInfo.instructions:
1. Imagery ============ You will use personalized **Mapgive Digital Globe the custom imagery** imagery for this zone. --- 2. Buildings ============ * **Be as precise as posible !** _Zoom to distinguish the buildings. Draw the building in its entirety even if it could be partially covered by trees._ ##**How ?** *With ID Editor :* 1. Use the tool **area** to draw the buildings 2. Once it's drawn, open the menu on the left of your page and search for "Type of buildings" category, then select **"buildings"** (this is the most generic name we could you, because it is not possible to know a more specific use of a building from a satelital imagery only) 3. Finally, correct the angles by taping **"S"** key ![how to map a building] (http://cartong.org/sites/cartong/files/GIF_Building_v2.gif) *With editor JOSM:* 1. Use tool **Draw nodes** to draw the buildings, or the pluggin **buildings_tools** 2. Then draw the byuildings and add the tag **building=yes** 3. Then, if you use "draw nodes" tool, think to correct the angles by pressing **"Q"** key. `Warning: many buildings are very close to each other but are not touch each other. Try to draw them close to each other without connect or share nodes between other buildings, roads or residential/natural areas. In ID Editor, you will avoid that the nodes get attracted and stuck to each other by pressing Alt key.` --- 3. Roads network ============ * **Please draw roads that are clearly visible** * **Connect the roads to the existing network** as much as possible. * **The very short roads that are not going anywhere should not be mapped** * **While drawing a road, overflow a bit your square** in order to let the person who will draw the square next to yours connect his roads to the existing network. `The classification of roads in Africa is different from the one of Western countries. The appearance and practicability of roads in African countries are not always representative of their economic and social role. In OSM, the typology of roads is based on the importance of roads and not on the state of their surface or their visual appearance. The typology proposed in OSM for African countries is based on a mapping experience on many of these countries, as well as many conversations and discussions, it is more adapted to the context of this continent. ` ##**For this project, we will use the following categories :** **Minor/unclassified road (unclassified) :** For roads on which a 4-wheeled vehicle could pass and connect small villages or hamlet. **Path :** For small roads on which a 4-wheeled vehicle could not pass and used by people on foot or on a two-wheeled vehicle. They can connect either not inhabited places or lead to cultivated fields. Only trace major roads that connect to populated places or other roads. **Track :** For smaller roads that leave residential areas, generally used for agricultural or forestry purposes. Most of the time these roads are not used to reach other roads. ##**How ?** *With ID Editor :* 1. Use **line** tool to draw the roads 2. Once you have drawn a road, go to the menu on the left, find the category that corresponds to the typology of the road or the path (see definition above) *With JOSM:* 1. Use **Draw nodes** tool to draw roads and paths 2. Draw the road and add the tag corresponding to its typologie. **Highway=Unclassified** or **Highway=path** or **Highway=track** (cf. definition above) --- **The mapping you do makes a real difference**: each of your contributions will not only be used by the organization that requested the project, but will also remain permanently in the OSM database and visible and reusable by all. Be as specific as possible! **Quality is more important than quantity!** Remember that cartography requires patience, attention and care.

**If you have questions, thank you for asking in the comment section**, one of our validators will be happy to answer!**, un de nos validateurs sera ravi de pouvoir y répondre !
